@D
It is unlike me to soap-box in these comments.

"despite these people existing outside of your singular existence." Even in the 1980's, I had friends who identified as bisexual, and shortly after that, knew folk who identified as transsexual--from drag, to medically transitioned (remember, gender reassignment procedures were much less available back then, and of course, not covered by medical insurance--a friend of mine worked three jobs to help pay for his partner's medical needs.) So, my existence, while singular, is not narrow.

But on to your second paragraph: "keep it simple." While I understand everyone's desire to be (singularly) recognized, the complexity of these labels, and multiplicity of these flags, only serves to alienate--yea, amuse--the moderate, and perhaps ignorant, segment of the population, and, in turn, gives ammunition to those "powerful forces" of which you write, and of which--singularly--I'm terrified. (I would argue this extends beyond gender politics, and the lack of cohesion within the left does little to advance its causes.)

@MOL--my understanding is that a fairly large segment of humanity--up to 10%, I've read--has something other than the XX/XY chromosome arrangement we were taught in HS Biology. A fact which should be trotted out more in defense of Trans Rights. (But who cares about scientific facts anymore?)

I hope y'all like They Might Be Giants, because I expect this, my second post, will be flagged and deleted.

